2340
01:32:31,320 --> 01:32:32,000
All right.

2341
01:32:33,220 --> 01:32:35,560
So let's go back to particle mechanics.

2342
01:32:36,400 --> 01:32:39,020
But particle mechanics in the presence of a field.

2343
01:32:39,639 --> 01:32:40,160
Okay.

2344
01:32:40,540 --> 01:32:41,580
So first of all,

2345
01:32:41,580 --> 01:32:44,260
we've already written down a Lagrangian for particle.

2346
01:32:44,820 --> 01:32:49,300
It was about the only thing available that was invariant.

2347
01:32:50,060 --> 01:32:52,740
And it was the integral of d tau.

2348
01:32:56,019 --> 01:32:58,380
For reasons of convention...

2349
01:32:58,380 --> 01:32:59,000
Well,

2350
01:32:59,000 --> 01:33:00,380
not just for reasons of convention.

2351
01:33:00,640 --> 01:33:03,300
But there was a parameter here which was called mass.

2352
01:33:03,940 --> 01:33:05,020
Which turned out,

2353
01:33:05,020 --> 01:33:05,440
in fact,

2354
01:33:05,440 --> 01:33:06,080
to be the mass.

2355
01:33:06,420 --> 01:33:08,040
We discovered that it behaved.

2356
01:33:08,040 --> 01:33:09,120
This is tau.

2357
01:33:09,420 --> 01:33:10,620
It did discover...

2358
01:33:10,620 --> 01:33:12,690
It behaved like a non-relativistic mass

2359
01:33:12,690 --> 01:33:14,760
when the particle was moving slowly.

2360
01:33:19,360 --> 01:33:20,980
And there was also a minus sign.

2361
01:33:22,960 --> 01:33:23,440
Surprisingly,

2362
01:33:23,440 --> 01:33:24,720
there was a minus sign there.

2363
01:33:24,940 --> 01:33:26,540
It always surprised me when I

2364
01:33:26,540 --> 01:33:28,140
was a young person learning this.

2365
01:33:28,300 --> 01:33:30,080
Why do you put the minus sign there?

2366
01:33:30,220 --> 01:33:30,680
Well,

2367
01:33:30,680 --> 01:33:32,750
you put the minus sign there so that when

2368
01:33:32,750 --> 01:33:34,820
you work it out and look at slow motion,

2369
01:33:36,200 --> 01:33:38,720
you get the right non-relativistic answer.

2370
01:33:38,880 --> 01:33:39,380
But this was it.

2371
01:33:41,220 --> 01:33:46,270
And d tau was the square root

2372
01:33:46,270 --> 01:33:51,320
of d t squared minus the x squared.

2373
01:33:56,000 --> 01:33:58,980
I keep telling you over and over again,

2374
01:33:58,980 --> 01:34:01,040
I won't write dy squared and dz squared,

2375
01:34:01,040 --> 01:34:01,820
and then I do it anyway.

2376
01:34:02,020 --> 01:34:02,200
Well,

2377
01:34:02,200 --> 01:34:03,460
I'm not going to do it.

2378
01:34:04,220 --> 01:34:04,660
Okay.

2379
01:34:05,539 --> 01:34:08,640
And then we divided by dt squared.

2380
01:34:08,900 --> 01:34:10,800
Put the dt out here.

2381
01:34:11,500 --> 01:34:17,060
Made this 1 minus dx squared over dt squared.

2382
01:34:17,380 --> 01:34:18,840
dx by dt squared.

2383
01:34:20,320 --> 01:34:22,000
And that was our Lagrangian.

2384
01:34:22,200 --> 01:34:24,160
It's a function of velocity.

2385
01:34:24,300 --> 01:34:26,640
We can also call this a velocity squared.

2386
01:34:31,240 --> 01:34:33,220
Also terms for y and z.

2387
01:34:33,660 --> 01:34:34,300
Okay.

2388
01:34:34,300 --> 01:34:36,120
This was our Lagrangian.

2389
01:34:36,460 --> 01:34:39,360
If we expanded it out for slow velocities,

2390
01:34:39,360 --> 01:34:41,300
we found out that it

2391
01:34:41,300 --> 01:34:43,240
was the good old Newtonian Lagrangian.

2392
01:34:43,900 --> 01:34:46,340
Good old conventional Lagrangian.

2393
01:34:46,520 --> 01:34:48,400
But this was it for relativity.

2394
01:34:49,260 --> 01:34:49,780
Now,

2395
01:34:49,780 --> 01:34:54,070
what can we do to this to

2396
01:34:54,070 --> 01:34:58,360
allow the particle to couple to a field?

2397
01:34:59,300 --> 01:35:01,700
Allow the particle to interact with the field,

2398
01:35:01,700 --> 01:35:03,240
be affected by the field?

2399
01:35:03,240 --> 01:35:04,040
Well,

2400
01:35:04,040 --> 01:35:05,530
in order for the particle

2401
01:35:05,530 --> 01:35:07,020
to be affected by the field,

2402
01:35:07,020 --> 01:35:10,120
we have to put into the Lagrangian the field somewheres.

2403
01:35:10,700 --> 01:35:13,100
We have to put it in

2404
01:35:13,100 --> 01:35:15,500
in a way that is Lorentz invariant.

2405
01:35:15,760 --> 01:35:16,780
In other words,

2406
01:35:16,780 --> 01:35:18,560
we want to put it in in a

2407
01:35:18,560 --> 01:35:20,340
way which is the same in every reference frame.

2408
01:35:21,080 --> 01:35:24,140
The only thing we have around involving fields,

2409
01:35:24,140 --> 01:35:26,800
which is the same in every reference frame,

2410
01:35:26,800 --> 01:35:27,500
is scalars.

2411
01:35:28,180 --> 01:35:30,740
There's lots of things we could do with scalars.

2412
01:35:30,780 --> 01:35:33,220
But one very simple thing we could do.

2413
01:35:33,220 --> 01:35:34,380
Would be,

2414
01:35:34,380 --> 01:35:38,840
well this was minus m d tau.

2415
01:35:40,680 --> 01:35:42,960
The simplest thing you can do is you

2416
01:35:42,960 --> 01:35:45,240
can say as the particle moves through the field,

2417
01:35:45,240 --> 01:35:47,600
you can add another term here,

2418
01:35:47,600 --> 01:35:50,520
which is the field times d tau.

2419
01:35:51,520 --> 01:35:52,800
There are many other things.

2420
01:35:52,900 --> 01:35:54,480
This is not unique by any means.

2421
01:35:54,900 --> 01:35:55,680
First of all,

2422
01:35:55,680 --> 01:35:56,930
you could add the square

2423
01:35:56,930 --> 01:35:58,180
of the field times d tau.

2424
01:35:58,380 --> 01:36:00,360
Or the cube of the field times d tau.

2425
01:36:00,680 --> 01:36:02,300
All of these would be quite legitimate.

2426
01:36:02,300 --> 01:36:06,760
Any function of the field times d tau.

2427
01:36:07,080 --> 01:36:09,560
But as far as the particle motion goes,

2428
01:36:09,560 --> 01:36:12,000
since we want to use invariants,

2429
01:36:12,000 --> 01:36:13,520
quantities which are invariant,

2430
01:36:13,520 --> 01:36:15,600
we want to use d tau.

2431
01:36:15,820 --> 01:36:19,140
It's the only thing around involving little

2432
01:36:19,140 --> 01:36:22,460
steps along the trajectory which is invariant.

2433
01:36:25,160 --> 01:36:25,820
So,

2434
01:36:25,820 --> 01:36:29,050
a possible Lagrangian would be to

2435
01:36:29,050 --> 01:36:32,280
add minus m plus m d tau.

2436
01:36:32,280 --> 01:36:34,260
Plus some function of the field phi.

2437
01:36:34,620 --> 01:36:36,020
Let's just call it plus phi.

2438
01:36:39,280 --> 01:36:42,030
There would be a possible Lagrangian for

2439
01:36:42,030 --> 01:36:44,780
a particle moving in a pre-established field.

2440
01:36:45,660 --> 01:36:48,300
For the moment the field has been given to us,

2441
01:36:48,300 --> 01:36:49,530
we're not going to ask how it

2442
01:36:49,530 --> 01:36:50,760
got to be the way it was.

2443
01:36:51,100 --> 01:36:55,600
We're asking how does the particle move in the field.

2444
01:36:56,900 --> 01:36:59,030
This is kind of like asking how a particle

2445
01:36:59,030 --> 01:37:01,160
moves in a magnetic field or an electric field.

2446
01:37:02,280 --> 01:37:02,280
So,

2447
01:37:02,280 --> 01:37:04,480
we're going to write down a Lagrangian for

2448
01:37:04,480 --> 01:37:06,680
the particle in the electric or magnetic field.

2449
01:37:06,800 --> 01:37:08,150
You don't worry about how the

2450
01:37:08,150 --> 01:37:09,500
electric or magnetic field got that way.

2451
01:37:10,860 --> 01:37:16,600
And this would be phi of x and t.

2452
01:37:17,980 --> 01:37:18,480
Alright,

2453
01:37:18,480 --> 01:37:21,290
I'm doing this first of all to illustrate

2454
01:37:21,290 --> 01:37:24,100
a point about interconnection between particles and fields.

2455
01:37:24,320 --> 01:37:25,520
But second of all,

2456
01:37:25,520 --> 01:37:26,040
just as a,

2457
01:37:26,040 --> 01:37:29,150
in order to do a little exercise and to

2458
01:37:29,150 --> 01:37:32,260
work out the equations of motion of the particle.

2459
01:37:33,180 --> 01:37:35,500
Let's work out the equations of motion of a particle.

2460
01:37:37,080 --> 01:37:38,240
Here's its Lagrangian.

2461
01:37:39,040 --> 01:37:40,960
And to work out its equations of motion,

2462
01:37:40,960 --> 01:37:43,280
we just do the Euler Lagrange equations of motion.

2463
01:37:43,520 --> 01:37:44,520
Let's just do them.

2464
01:37:45,340 --> 01:37:46,040
They're ugly.

2465
01:37:46,040 --> 01:37:46,800
They're not nice.

2466
01:37:46,800 --> 01:37:47,580
They're not pretty.

2467
01:37:47,940 --> 01:37:49,960
Does phi have to be in the integral?

2468
01:37:50,960 --> 01:37:51,400
Yes,

2469
01:37:51,400 --> 01:37:51,820
I'm sorry.

2470
01:37:51,820 --> 01:37:53,040
Phi should be in the integral.

2471
01:37:53,040 --> 01:37:53,680
Absolutely.

2472
01:37:57,880 --> 01:37:59,440
Unless it's a function of only x,

2473
01:37:59,440 --> 01:37:59,820
right?

2474
01:38:00,100 --> 01:38:00,540
Yeah.

2475
01:38:00,540 --> 01:38:02,260
Unless it's a function only of x.

2476
01:38:04,680 --> 01:38:05,240
That's correct.

2477
01:38:05,240 --> 01:38:07,740
Unless it happens to be just a function of x.

2478
01:38:08,400 --> 01:38:11,000
But that x represents the position of the particle?

2479
01:38:11,340 --> 01:38:12,750
This represents the position of

2480
01:38:12,750 --> 01:38:14,160
the particle at the time t.

2481
01:38:14,220 --> 01:38:14,420
Yes,

2482
01:38:14,420 --> 01:38:15,880
it should be in the integral.

2483
01:38:15,880 --> 01:38:17,620
It has to be in the integral.

2484
01:38:19,480 --> 01:38:23,640
Because even though phi might not depend on t,

2485
01:38:23,640 --> 01:38:26,360
x depends on t.

2486
01:38:26,580 --> 01:38:28,980
So phi of x depends on t.

2487
01:38:28,980 --> 01:38:31,240
So it's phi of x and t.

2488
01:38:31,240 --> 01:38:32,260
It's inside the integral.

2489
01:38:32,260 --> 01:38:33,460
Right.

2490
01:38:37,760 --> 01:38:38,960
Now first of all,

2491
01:38:38,960 --> 01:38:40,520
notice something interesting about this.

2492
01:38:41,780 --> 01:38:45,460
Supposing for some reason the field

2493
01:38:45,460 --> 01:38:49,140
liked to migrate to some value.

2494
01:38:49,320 --> 01:38:52,810
For some reason the field liked to

2495
01:38:52,810 --> 01:38:56,300
seek some stable value which wasn't zero.

2496
01:38:58,420 --> 01:39:01,020
Supposing it liked to get frozen for some reason.

2497
01:39:02,060 --> 01:39:02,920
Why would it get frozen?

2498
01:39:02,920 --> 01:39:04,400
Because phi of x is a constant.

2499
01:39:04,900 --> 01:39:06,740
It's a constant of x,

2500
01:39:06,740 --> 01:39:10,420
because phi is a constant of x.

2501
01:39:10,500 --> 01:39:15,320
The particle is going to be a constant of x.

2502
01:39:15,320 --> 01:39:15,800
And phi is going to be a constant of x.

2503
01:39:16,280 --> 01:39:17,380
Because x is a constant of x.

2504
01:39:17,380 --> 01:39:19,600
So phi of y is going

2505
01:39:19,600 --> 01:39:21,820
to be a constant of x.

2506
01:39:21,820 --> 01:39:22,200
And phi of x is going

2507
01:39:22,200 --> 01:39:22,580
to be a constant of x.

2508
01:39:22,580 --> 01:39:22,620
Well,

2509
01:39:22,620 --> 01:39:24,520
if you put phi of x in the integral,

2510
01:39:24,520 --> 01:39:29,140
what does phi do?

2511
01:39:29,140 --> 01:39:30,470
It does something.

2512
01:39:30,470 --> 01:39:33,470
would be m minus phi.

2513
01:39:33,470 --> 01:39:38,150
This is the simplest example of how a scalar field

2514
01:39:38,150 --> 01:39:40,090
can give rise to a shift

2515
01:39:40,090 --> 01:39:42,030
of the mass of a particle.

2516
01:39:42,030 --> 01:39:44,450
What,

2517
01:39:44,450 --> 01:39:45,810
I said there was going

2518
01:39:45,810 --> 01:39:46,810
to be an exam at the end,

2519
01:39:46,810 --> 01:39:49,110
what field is most like this in nature?

2520
01:39:49,110 --> 01:39:50,510
Sure,

2521
01:39:50,510 --> 01:39:52,130
yeah,

2522
01:39:52,130 --> 01:39:52,950
the

2523
01:39:52,950 --> 01:39:54,850
Higgs field is the thing which is

2524
01:39:54,850 --> 01:39:56,750
most like this scalar field in nature,

2525
01:39:56,750 --> 01:39:57,790
and you

2526
01:39:57,790 --> 01:40:00,050
can see how it's possible that if

2527
01:40:00,050 --> 01:40:02,310
the Higgs field gets shifted by some

2528
01:40:02,310 --> 01:40:02,870
mechanism,

2529
01:40:02,870 --> 01:40:05,030
its value gets shifted,

2530
01:40:05,030 --> 01:40:06,430
in turn it will shift the

2531
01:40:06,430 --> 01:40:07,830
value of the mass of a

2532
01:40:07,830 --> 01:40:08,170
particle.

2533
01:40:08,170 --> 01:40:10,230
In fact,

2534
01:40:10,230 --> 01:40:15,010
if the mass of some particle naturally began as zero,

2535
01:40:15,010 --> 01:40:16,650
but it

2536
01:40:16,650 --> 01:40:18,010
was coupled to this field phi,

2537
01:40:18,010 --> 01:40:21,790
and this field phi naturally sought some

2538
01:40:21,790 --> 01:40:22,810
particular value,

2539
01:40:22,810 --> 01:40:26,970
the particle would effectively have a mass which would be

